A black box in your car?
While U.S. road network planners are struggling to find the money needed to repair the depleted highway infrastructure, many are those who have an idea of a solution in the form of a small black box that’s fixed above your car’s dashboard.
The devices, which record every mile travelled by a driver and transmit information to officials, are at the heart of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government offices of planning to remake the outdated funding system for major U.S. roads.
The generally uninterested sector of major axis planning has suddenly provoked a heated debate and agitated alliances.
Liberals have joined environmental groups to pressure so that the government uses the small boxes to keep track of the miles you walk, and possibly the road you drive on, and then use the information to write a tax bill.
The Tea Party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses concern about privacy protection.
And while members of Congress are unable to agree on whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles they have travelled.
Thousands of drivers have already embarked on these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental turn.
This is very important for our nation.
"It's not like we had the choice," said Hasan Ikhrata, general director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which predicts that the state will start recording the miles travelled by each California driver by 2025.
There will be a change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do that.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded with taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans no longer buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars can travel more than miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transport policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed tracks on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
“This turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative,” he said.
Wonks calls this mileage usage cost.
It’s not surprising that the idea attracts urban liberals, as taxes could be used to change driving habits to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to the goals set in the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also saw it as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market supporters of the Reason Foundation also appreciate the idea of getting drivers paid by mile.
“It’s not just a tax plunging into a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of politics at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go the way of paying the mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would cover about 10,000 cars.
But the House Presidency killed the proposal, responding to concerns from rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to work or town.
However, several states and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which mobilized 5,000 drivers to conduct the country’s most important experience.
These drivers will soon pay the state kilometre fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is considering one.
Illinois is testing a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 Coalition, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transportation in states along the U.S. East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida) is studying how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer drivers recently equipped their cars with a device, drivers were worried that the government could follow their slightest deeds and gestures.
“The concerns about Big Brother and things like this are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
This is not something people want.
From the start of the test, the Nevada ACLU warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged localization devices.”
There is no need to build a huge, crowded technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people’s daily passages and arrivals.
Nevada is one of the few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car runs, but without knowing the exact place or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to use a small California start-up called True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to help drivers who pay taxes to states.
She sought to break into the emerging car insurance market, where drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices she tests liked big axis planners because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically downloaded by modem.
“People will be more inclined to do this if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in pilot programs in some states.
There are far less expensive methods and far less intrusive methods to do so.
In Oregon, planners try the experiment by offering drivers different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They can still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles travelled by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transport managers are seeking to develop a taxation device that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide a “driving payment” insurance and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Drivers would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits that the system offers them,” said a document on urban planning.
However, some transport planners wonder if the whole debate about paying by mile isn’t just a huge distraction.
At the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very simply manage the Highway Trust Fund bankruptcy by raising gasoline taxes.
A single or annual additional tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume much gasoline, so that everyone pays their fair share.
“There is no need to resort to radical surgery when you simply need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, the commission’s director of legislation and public affairs.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
David Bowie: Four unprecedented hits
The musician did not stop surprising this year.
Starting with The Next Day, which was released in January, he made up a luxury re-release scheduled for November 4, with several unpublished ones.
Four of them have already appeared on the Internet.
The announcement of a new album by David Bowie has left everyone in shock.
On his 66th birthday, on January 8, 2013, he announced that a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dated 2003) and too few public appearances, the English musician proved that one could still count on him to scintillate the pop scene.
A party for fans
Not surprisingly, David Bowie had more than one round in his bag with The Next Day.
Thin White Duke are scheduled to re-release the album on November 4.
In the meantime, he planned a big party for his fans.
This re-release, titled The Next Day Extra, will come in the form of three albums: the original album, unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four clips already unveiled.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional titles compared to the original album: the three songs from the Deluxe edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie has presented this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces both each of the discs, but also the accessories provided with: exclusive photos and cover, a booklet to share his own impressions, a booklet with the words...
And, most importantly, he gives a taste of his new Atomica title, typically in the vein of The Next Day, with very forward guitars and skillfully mastered rock electricity.
Unknown people are listening
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like a Rocket Man, Born in a UFO are also available online.
The Informer is double-faced: a disturbing introduction before a bright riding that gradually slows down to give way to a pop ballad.
On Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a little reference to Elton John’s Rocket Man, or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems at least in his element when he no longer has his feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born in a UFO, David Bowie once again refers to his weirdness: Would he come from another planet?
Guitar riffs, enchanting, make you want to leave the Earth.
Bowie enjoys playing the cameleon with these titles: turn-by-turn informant, man on a rocket, potential martian...
He hides and reveals both, playing to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
It is not surprising that he has a mask in his hand in the photograph of the campaign The Invitation to Travel, of the Louis Vuitton brand, whose new face he embodies.
It will appear in one of their advertising spots, broadcasting from November 10.
Defense Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that the wounded soldiers were not summarily released from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was followed by all soldiers before they returned to civilian life.
Attacked by liberals and neo-democrats in the House of Commons, Nicholson assured that before their release, members of the army were following a transition plan in collaboration with their superiors.
