Horses in beef products
Horse meat was detected in conserve boxes of beef products sold by two small British low-cost distribution brands, the food hygiene agency announced today.
Routine tests revealed that the products, developed in January in Romania and sold by the Home Bargains and Quality Save chains, contained horse DNA up to 1-5%.
"Since horse meat is not mentioned in the ingredient list, it should not have been present in the product," the agency said.
A scandal about the presence of horse meat in cooked dishes broke out in Europe earlier this year, following tests carried out in Ireland.
According to the European Commission, France was the country most affected by the presence of this type of meat in products that are supposed to contain only beef.
