Frontier Airlines plans to pay for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to pay up to $100 for passengers carrying hand luggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to start paying up to $100 for a hand luggage and $2 for a coffee or soda, although in its Wednesday announcement it said passengers could take the unopened can with them when the plane landed.
The new hand luggage fee applies to bags stored in the upper compartment, so small bags installed underneath the seat will always be free.
Frontier said it would pay $25 if the fees were paid in advance and $100 if travellers only paid once at the boarding door.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 was planned to encourage travellers to pay the fees in advance.
“We don’t want to pay that price,” she said.
The airlines began paying for the first and second baggage registered in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges put as many things as they could in the hand luggage stored in the upper compartments, so there was often no more space in those compartments.
These charges are a way to ensure that passengers carry fewer things on board.
O'Malley said these new fees won't really be used to raise money.
It is about making the most loyal customers of Frontier understand that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the upper compartments.
Passengers who purchase their tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
Thus, a passenger in the queue at a Frontier boarding door could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O’Malley explained that Frontier’s site and registration procedures are changing to ensure passengers are aware of the existence of these charges before they arrive at the door.
Frontier hand luggage charges will not be applied before summer, although no date has been set.
Passengers often hesitate about luggage charges and other charges, but airlines love them.
They believe that the cost of handling luggage is significant and that passengers who want this service should pay for it.
Many people on Wall Street consider the addition of luggage fees to be a sign that airlines are paying expensive enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
Many of them did not pay for luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. applied the first hand luggage charges three years ago, and the low-cost airline Allegiant followed a little later.
The only other airline that imposes such charges is the Hungarian airline Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the charges as a supplement.
In a December 2011 report, he estimated that Spirit’s hand luggage costs amounted to $50 million a year.
