NSA blames “internal error” and not hackers for failing its website
The National Security Agency operating in the shadow said Friday it was a bug that had caused its public website to break down for a few hours, and not hackers as some claimed online.
“NSA.gov remained inaccessible for a few hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during a planned update,” the agency said in an email statement.
The problem will be resolved tonight.
The allegations that the failure was due to a distributed denial of service [DSD] attack are false.
Earlier tonight, online server trackers noted that the NSA site had been down for at least 6 hours, and some users still can’t access the site.
Earlier, a NSA spokesman told ABC News that the agency’s sensitive internal network was “not at all” compromised.
No classified information is at risk, the spokesman said.
At least one group of online hacktivists claimed to be responsible for the failure of the NSA site by a DSD attack.
DSD attacks aim to flood a targeted site until the servers are overloaded and the site crashes.
Cyber tactics are not very sophisticated and attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the targeted system.
The once ultra-secret NSA, once nicknamed the “No Such Agency,” has been blasted and heavily criticized in recent months following a wave of disclosures about its extensive communications surveillance programs at home and abroad – which are part of the NSA’s secret files stolen from the agency and disclosed by the disappointed former NSA consultant, Edward Snowden.
This growing controversy around the agency has sparked a lot of speculation that the incident tonight was the result of a targeted cyber-operation.
