Bombardier profits decline as aircraft deliveries and orders decline
Bombardier Inc, a Canadian aircraft and railway manufacturer, a 15% drop in its net profit on Thursday, under pressure from falling aircraft orders and deliveries in the third quarter and contractual problems in its Train division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, has also not provided flight test data for its all-new CSeries aircraft, nor information on whether the aircraft will meet its ambitious commercial launch schedule before next September.
After the initial flight of the test aircraft about a month and a half ago, the latter flew only three times, and then the question arose whether the test phase was on the right track.
The results did not meet expectations and the stock price fell 8% on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
