However, one interesting point has been forgotten in this interpretation of an old dusty tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow the instructions of Europe, in fact?
Why exchange the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe is finally at a dead end.
With the crisis of the euro, the Project Europe is officially dead.
Thro Europe, parties that oppose the EU or advocate the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and coming from nowhere, gathered almost five million votes in the September federal elections and removed the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been a national opposition to the project of creating a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the burden on national economies through membership in the single currency, has led many to think that the Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments having excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
Instead, the European system has imposed on its members favorable exchange rates for German exporters – which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, the countries of Southern Europe are facing an inherent productivity problem with Germany.
The only remedy is to make dark cuts in wages and public spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is deeper productivity unrest in Europe.
Following the “green” energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas than the United States.
This is a redhibitory disadvantage in terms of cost, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the world’s wage freezes won’t prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap U.S. shale gas.
As a result, the revolt crumbled, especially in France, one of the great leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a means of controlling Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport for its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the troubled French economy to disappear.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s far-right party, the anti-European National Front, just won a crucial partial election, bringing the socialists in power back to the third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot rely on the principle that a split from the right will automatically favor the left.
What does Marine Le Pen do with her new popularity with the French white working class?
She wants to use the European elections next year to create a single anti-European anti-currency bloc within the European Parliament.
If anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is very likely, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I think: very soon, the anti-European and anti-currency sentiment in Europe will unify and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something that will more resemble the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” freely favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies could retain the euro, but France and Southern Europe will regain their own currency.
I expect the UK to take its distance from this project, and I hope it will make the eyes gentle in the United States.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of small England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending around Berlin and Brussels.
I believe that Scotland could accommodate a more free European agreement if we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other countries with similar views would be easier in a non-federal Europe of Nations.
Otherwise, we should imitate Norway and maintain our economic independence.
The Scottish SNP government is – and is to be noted – the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, since it won a spectacular majority in 2011 based on its opposition to the dark cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor Alistair Darling, and the Conservatives/Liberal Democrats coalition that followed.
It would be ridiculous now for Scotland to vote for independence if it is to accept the austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Ageing Early
Studies show that young African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
Physical changes don’t mean puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts think obesity epidemic could be a trigger for early puberty
The tendency to early puberty is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother worry if her daughter’s breasts and pubic hair start to grow at age 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, a pediatric endocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young American women and represent a new standard.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – generally, this doesn’t indicate a rapid progression to full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as swollen breasts, hair under the arms and in the pubic area and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age of first menstruation over the last four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half years, compared to 12 years three-quarters in 1970.
“Once the breast has begun to grow, it takes at least two or three years before the first periods appear,” said Kaplowitz, also the author of “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to coping with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test for how puberty will evolve.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered “early” when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, development slows down or stops – this is something a pediatrician can follow closely.
A faster progression may justify tests performed by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first period and prevent other consequences: premature ageing of bones that can slow growth and small size in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormonal treatment are based on the age of the child, development rate, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
The psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious with drugs but acknowledges that “controlling puberty can alleviate certain behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others.”
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don’t want their very young girls to have their periods.
“They’re worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they’re going to handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period at the age of 10.
Even if there were signs and we had talked about the rules, she wasn’t emotionally prepared.
She came home from school frightened and upset by being the first of her friends.
There are many theories brought to the public knowledge about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent theory that the hormones contained in milk or other foods, chemicals present in the environment, or sexual messages transmitted by the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the most credible hypothesis is that of the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study conducted on girls aged 6 to 9 that linked the percentage of fat mass to the trigger of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty seem to be influenced by everything, from economic conditions to climate, through genes.
Another problem: Although boys have younger hair on the face and in the pubic area, the tendency towards true early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference insisted on the complexity of the subject.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common, even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist working at the Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean having a conversation sooner than expected,” Kaplowitz said.
If you stay calm, your child will generally react well.
Girls whose puberty is early should be reassured that, even when it happens sooner than expected, the process is part of life.
