Although she earns $3,000 from Singapore ($2,400) a month as an administrator and her husband works as well, the monthly family income isn’t enough, she says.
In fact, demand is such in some parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – that ValueMax, where it made its transaction, became this week the third mortgage lending company to be introduced to the Singapore Stock Exchange.
Borrowing jewelry is not only a quick way to get cash – $1,300 from Singapore in the case of Ms. Amirthalinga – but it’s almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
In general, Singapore’s mortgage lenders charge an effective annual interest rate of 17%, just above the 15.4% offered by the United Overseas Bank, a local fund lender with a branch in the same shopping center.
However, mortgage lenders have the advantage of not asking for a solvency check or salary proof, and can unlock loans faster than banks.
As a result, millions of people across the region turn to mortgage lenders as families feel the pressure of rising cost of living and overindebted households and consumers.
After five years of strong growth since the global financial crisis, and cheap credit fuelled by too lax monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to mortgage lenders to fill the gap as their economies experience a slowdown.
This week, rating agency Standard & Poor's cited the rising household debt, mainly due to the rise in mortgages, as a risk factor for the solvency of Asian banks.
She said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore recorded the highest household debt/GDP ratio in Asia.
