The announcement by the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OIAC) has arrived a day ahead of the deadline.
On November 1, the Hague-based organization ordered Damascus to destroy or “make unusable” all chemical weapons production units and machinery for mixing toxic gases and filling ammunition.
The completion of what is essentially the initial phase of destruction is an important step in the ambitious calendar aimed at destroying Damascus’ chemical weapons by mid-2014.
Because of the destruction of equipment, Syria will no longer be able to produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus still has to begin the destruction of existing weapons and reserves.
It is estimated that the country has about 1,000 tons of chemical products and weapons, including mustard gas and the neurotoxic agent sarin.
