FAA: Airline passengers can now use gadgets on board planes (but not make a call with their mobile phones)
Airline passengers will be able to use their door-to-door electronic devices to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music – but not talk on their mobile phones – under the much-anticipated new guidelines released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers should not expect immediate changes.
The speed with which the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, FAA administrator Michael Huerta said at a news conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA that their aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated crew training manuals and aircraft storage rules to comply.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of electronic devices on their planes.
Delta and JetBlue are among the companies that have already submitted plans.
“Depending on the plan, we could approve widespread use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the doors of the plane are closed.
They are not supposed to turn them on until the plane reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the commander gives its green light.
Passengers are supposed to turn off their aircraft when the aircraft descends before landing and not re-enable them until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new directives, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during takeoffs, landings and landing, the FAA said.
Most new aircraft and other aircraft that have been modified so passengers can use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, was pleased with these changes.
“Once the new policy is safely implemented – and we will work closely with carriers to do so – it will benefit everyone,” Glading said in a statement.
We’re frankly tired of feeling like “room watchers” when it comes to this issue.
But it will still be forbidden to connect to the Internet to surf, exchange emails and SMS, or download data below 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will have to put their smartphones, tablets and other devices in airplane mode.
So still not Words With Friends, the Scrabble-style online game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011 when he was thrown out loud from an American Airlines plane after refusing to turn off his device while the aircraft was parked at the door.
And heavier devices like laptops will always have to be stored as they could injure someone if they flew through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also be banned.
The regulatory power regarding mobile phones belongs to the Federal Communications Commission and not the FAA.
The FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert on CBS News, said mobile phones were still considered to pose a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could eventually create interference with navigation instruments, but because we know, according to the FCC, that they could disrupt mobile phone relay antennas if used on board,” Rosenker said.
An industrial advisory committee set up by the FAA to examine the issue recommended last month that the government allow for wider use of personal electronics.
The pressure on the FAA has intensified in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there is no valid safety reason for these bans.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that at least one-third of passengers forget to turn off their devices, or do so deliberately.
The FAA began limiting the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports of interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers carried FM radios, the high-tech gadget of the time.
New aircraft rely much more on electric systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand electronic interference and approved by the FAA.
Airlines have allowed their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruise altitudes for several years.
Airplanes modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems are also better resistant to interference.
The vast majority of commercial aircraft are expected to allow for wider use of electronic devices under the new directives, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit radio transmissions of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, emit only minimal transmissions when a page is turned.
But transmissions are stronger when devices download or send data.
Amazon.com is among those who are pushing for easing restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers.
In 2011, the company’s executives loaded a Kindle e-book reader line-up plane and drove it off to see if there were any problems, but there was none.
This has inspired members of the FAA Advisory Committee to have mixed feelings about whether or not the use of the devices presents a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he thought the interference from the aircraft was real, even though the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee said there are only anecdotal reports from pilots that indicate that aircraft can interfere with aircraft systems, and that most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to ask passengers to turn off their aircraft during instrument landings in low-visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes, calling them common sense arrangements for technology-equipped travelers.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not incompatible with safety,” said Roger Dow, President and Director of the U.S. Travel Association.
