Is the European elite ready to do business with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise of bringing companies together and defining what wealth and job creators want to see change in our relationship with the EU.
To do this, we ordered the broadest and most comprehensive survey from UK business leaders and asked them what they thought of Britain, and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1,000 business leaders, globally representative of all sizes of, sectors and regions in the UK.
The findings of the investigation will surprise many.
We found that the vast majority of companies are now looking to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernizing and developing while EU states are stagnant.
They want to see the government prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil rather than slide into the long and arduous process of reforming the European institutional arcanums.
When asked for their opinion on specific policy issues – ranging from monopoly regulation to product laws – most business executives think that the control of these key skills should go back to Westminster.
The single market has caused general discontent, with companies saying the cost of the Brussels Regulation is disproportionate to the benefits of being part of the European Trade Area – 40% of large companies, traditionally the most pro-European, even agree.
Finally, our survey of business leaders revealed that a significant majority wanted Britain to pursue initiatives to change the treaty and develop a relationship with the EU based on trade rather than politics.
This conclusion, which can be found in all major groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the business world insists on a “significant change” that brings power back to the UK.
The stakes are high – reaching a change in the treaty and better representing Britain’s interests would see a 16% swing of votes in favour of the country’s stay in the EU in a referendum.
The prime minister should not doubt for a moment: this survey shows that British companies are supporting this plan to renegotiate the terms of Britain’s EU membership.
It also shows that companies hope that the renegotiation will constitute a significant shift in the current balance of power in favor of a return to the UK.
It is possible, and increasingly necessary, to better represent the interests of British companies as the euro area is committed to a closer economic and fiscal union.
Employment and growth in the UK must be the priority and, as our survey findings show, for companies this means re-focusing on trade and a fundamental change in Brussels’ regulatory approach.
