Two YMCA employees accused of sexual assault following allegations made against Jonathan Lord during a royal commission hearing.
Two New South Wales YMCA employees were accused of sexual assault against children following allegations made against Caringbah educator Jonathan Lord in 2011 during a hearing by the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse.
But in its opening statement to the Commission, the YMCA said it had “never had to deal with a problem of sexual assault on children within its organization.”
Chief Executive Phillip Hare was questioned on two cases: an employee of the YMCA was accused of child pornography offenses and a physical education monitor at the YMCA Caringbah Hall was found guilty of sexual assault on children in the center where he worked in 1991.
Mr. Hare told Gail Furness, a lawyer at the Commission, that he was aware of the first case but was unaware of the second.
He also admitted that the YMCA opening statement was inaccurate, emphasizing, “YMCA external checks were carried out and indicated that children’s safety was an absolute priority for the organization.”
It was demonstrated to the Commission that the YMCA had been informed that it had received the second worst ratings on four institutions during a quality audit conducted by the Department of Education and Communities in August of this year.
Mr. Hare, who began working at YMCA at the age of 21, admitted that staff management was a failure with Lord’s recruitment and that he had omitted to check that employees knew they were required to report any violations of the Children’s Safety Policy.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sexual assault on twelve boys during the two years he worked at the YMCA.
He was sentenced to a minimum sentence of six years in prison.
But Mr. Hare rejected the idea that the YMCA would have a cultural problem preventing staff from reporting Lord’s misconduct towards children’s safety.
Staff members testified that they had noticed certain shortcomings, including the fact that Lord was staying alone with the children, keeping them private, making them sit on his knees, telling them he loved them and letting them play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Ockwell, who was led by Lord and who had sought child protection training because she was concerned about her behavior, said she found YMCA Caringbah’s head of child care Jacqui Barnat, who ran Lord “very intimidating and difficult to approach most of the time.”
The CEO said he rejected staff testimony that they were reluctant to report these shortcomings to their hierarchical superior.
Instead, he stated that the friendly relations they had with Lord have blurred their judgment, causing them not to report his actions.
Mr. Hare said he had expressed his point of view before the New South Wales YMCA board saying that, for the organization, the lesson drawn from the “Jonathan Lord incident” should not be about “reporting” by staff, and the board agreed with him.
Mr. Hare said the decision to have staff sign confidentiality agreements, shortly after the allegations were cited, was made by YMCA’s chief child care officer, Liam Whitley.
He said the decision was intended to avoid any contamination of evidence but that it was “excessive zeal” and that it had been misimplemented.
The New South Wales YMCA was not a safe organization for children at the time Jonathan Lord was employed there, namely between 2009 and 2011, said the expert on sexual violence against children, Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University to the Commission.
