How biometrics will invade our lives
Have you finished the passwords to enter to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future in which we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that “the century will be biometric.”
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person making transactions in a transversal and transnational universe like the Internet.
Privacy organisations confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned.
Only in 2011 and in France, the National Commission of Informatics and Freedoms authorized 774 fingerprint, hand shape or venous hand network recognition systems in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington.
What is the reason for such optimism in some and pessimism in others?
Biometrics will be based on new technologies, which will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
Each of these techniques has its limitations.
“For example, some people who work concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable,” says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity field at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - one cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure sometimes needs to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for about twenty years on other approaches, such as face recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of sensors and the computing capability of computers needed for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has multiplied by ten over the past five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and the Netherlands have deployed automatic border checkpoints using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
As a unique and infallible marker, DNA also arouses hopes and concerns.
“In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data,” says Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospects at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers criminal police services a suitcase costing €90,000 to analyze DNA samples on the scene of a crime and within an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing a person among others) and authentication (assuring that the person is who they claim to be).
Identification previously concerned the issuance of identity papers: biometric elements (fingerprints, photo, iris) must be compared with the information that the state has about all citizens already registered.
This ensures that one person is not trying to usurp someone else’s identity.
This comparison principle may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
“We are retrieving images from surveillance cameras and comparing them to photos of celebrities that are circulating freely on the Internet,” said Dany Nassif, head of commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Other uses: take a photo of a quidam who is in the queue in a store, track its progress through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Initially, authentication concerned physical access (boundaries, protected premises, cantines...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, presence control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the friend pointing for another," justifies Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also affect transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some dealers by inserting his card and placing his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces typing the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and large distribution brands: when paying in the store with his bank card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger in a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tips to Reassure Users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in the box thirty seconds less, it is valuable," explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you tailored options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect the databases.
"Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people's identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which locks up if one tries to move it," lists Philippe Robin, of Thales.
But, in the absence of extensive studies, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
Privacy experts are still worried.
“The advances in facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
