Scientists have just revealed how the movements of a dog’s tail are related to his mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved it more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trente, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left and right side of the brain are differently involved in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what was happening in other species.
He added that just like in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to other dogs’ disorderly tail movements, the researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with films depicting other dogs – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other factor of confusion – and we were able to trade the tail movement and present it as going more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw an expressionless dog moving its tail to the right (from the viewpoint of the dog moving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they noticed a tail deviating mainly to the left (again from the dog’s point of view moving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs deliberately communicated with each other through these movements.
Instead, he thinks that dogs know by experience what movements they should or should not worry about.
He added, “If you meet other dogs repeatedly and you notice that most of the time their tail movement to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side results in a less friendly attitude, you will react according to that experience.”
The researchers say the findings could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better grasp the emotions of their pets.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a guest professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the dog species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University found that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs went more easily toward a robot dog when its tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what was shown in the Italian study.”
He said the differences could come from the fact that the dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully regard the animals in the movies or robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“Al many evidence, found in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it will not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
