The election ended with a overwhelming victory, and newspaper presenters took the time to reflect on the historical nature of the moment.
My comrades wept of joy and my parents kept all the newspapers they found.
A young team of visionaries was advancing towards the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During Obama's transitional period before taking office in 2008, he had 82% favorable opinions.
Then I close the book.
Return to the present is a difficult awakening, it is like getting out of a dream.
It is hard to remember those days full of optimism, they are like distant memories, a sad reminder of opportunities from the past.
The change really happened in the years that followed the first time I voted.
It had nothing to do with what I had imagined.
I credit Obama with great achievements, from the passing of the Affordable Care Act to the departure of our army from Iraq, through the end of the “neither seen nor known” and the assassination of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that partisan obstructionism has destroyed too many efforts to advance our nation in the field of immigration reforms, public health care and the closure of Guantanamo, among other things.
But after repeatedly defending the Obama administration in front of my peers and colleagues, I can no longer provide any explanations.
I am on the verge of political despair.
Republican obstruction cannot explain the intercepting of foreign leaders, nor the attacks of innocent foreign children by drones.
It cannot explain that the National Security Agency is collecting data on the privacy of Americans, nor the prosecution of whistleblowers who reveal the government’s misconduct.
It cannot justify the murder of Anwar al-Awlaki, a U.S. citizen, without trial, or the evasion of public funding and excess spending permitted during the presidential campaign.
It cannot justify the conclusions of a report that says the White House’s efforts to silence the media are the “most aggressive... since the Nixon administration.”
And, more recently, it can’t excuse the inability to design a simple website for more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was ratified.
I don’t know if that was what I expected.
If, at the age of 18, I was supposed to understand that governance could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the electoral function is not predictable, as the opposition political party and random events, such as the Newton massacre, influence our public conversation.
However, all of the examples I listed above seem to be largely the administration’s choice.
That is what annoys me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and unrefined alternative that did not seem to allow determining his policies or positions.
I felt that Obama, elected for a second term by being freed from the pressure of future elections, would keep the promises that have been heard for so long.
However, while the positive opinion index dropped below 45% this week, it’s even harder to go back to 2008 through this book.
He made me wish for the many promises that have flown away.
This week, I read the part of the book that describes how Obama suffered enormous losses to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primaries.
At a post-campaign meeting, he told his team that they needed to get back on the right track and stay loyal to their cause.
“I want us to reconsider our talent,” he said.
We need to remember who we are.
Five years later, I disagree with you.
The views expressed in this comment are only those of Nathaniel Morris.
