A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new species of bush dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, Scientific Mission Officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Marine Environments (OCEAMM), returns to L’Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Are you surprised by the discovery of this new species of dolphin?
This is good news, but I am not surprised.
If in the past species were described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allow us to improve our knowledge in the sciences of species classification.
It is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to question the classification or belonging of a species to a gender, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on the morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are questioned due to the advances of genetics.
Similarly, two very closely related species morphologically have been distinguished through genetics.
This is the case for the new species that has just been identified.
About a decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific bush dolphins and Atlantic bush whales.
Recent studies have distinguished four species.
Why is this an important discovery as claimed by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population was already known for a long time by the researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral outbreak or accidental capture arises in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered endangered or endangered depending on the number of individuals on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility that it has to recover from neighboring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, from which the population of the newly discovered species is derived, its stock has automatically become weaker, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene mixing limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, closer ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the sea environment is the least known.
One would rather send robots to Mars than know what lives in the Mariana pit, just 11 kilometers from the sea surface.
More money is spent on the search for life on other planets than on marine research, and it’s time for that to change.
