Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents to Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the ink and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies de Satie.
A evening that allows you to see all the prisma of Chouinard, from art to tics and black from ink to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white as it is, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, stands, of profile, thin as a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink of Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple trait, takes its shape.
And this shape will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, with only their hands and face uncovered, wait on each side of the play area, rush when the next graphic appears, embody it, run out running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is made in solos relays, in unison groups (a mass that is solo), in a large group of twelve solos where each performs its sign.
We think of "Gloire du matin", where, in solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, placed in line at the front stage.
This is the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussions and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur will take refuge under the dance carpet, to deliver, micro in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux’s poem, monochrome and monotonous in the cry, and will continue dancing.
And the music to resume, and the sequence to resume.
This long, noisy and energetic discharge, if possible, ends up dulling and thickening.
The same applies to the visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes—imaging has always been a force in Chouinard—like those hair that blink or those black fabrics that stretch the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux’s work, has imposed itself, with his tics.
The result: the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’ ink, like Gestalt forms, opens up a wider, more porous imaginary than dance.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers shaved by a stroboscopic light and the white signs in a suddenly black theatre, touches magic.
The audience loved it and the reception was warm.
The gymnastics, after the interruption, is richer.
The scene is partially drawn in gray, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in an abandoned house.
At the piano, dancers rejoice to play the partitions.
Their mistakes in music, touching, give a real fragility.
On stage, the couples pass, in loving duos, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving sets, choirs, writing is less binary.
Bouffons appear, also familiar to Chouinard, with a red nose, in highly polarized male-female love parades.
Lovers are carnivores, fugitives or gamers.
The gestures, laughter and small cries beautifully transpose the archaic, grace and ridicule of the bodies in coit, of beings who merge.
But the piece takes its real flight after the salvation.
A clown returns to the stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permitted: the fourth wall falls, the universes explored overlap, the dancers cabotine, descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce into a wisely calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness sweat, and it is Chouinard’s art, there, to contaminate the public.
