He walks through mud, jungle and rivers to offer free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free health care in Cameroon villages
Dr. Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend seeing hundreds of patients.
There are not many doctors in this West African country, just 1 per 5,000 inhabitants.
Vote here or via your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 CNN Heroes of the Year 2013.
You can vote for him, or one of the 10 other heroes, to elect him “CNN Hero of the Year.”
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternate periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and go to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma of which he would bear the consequences for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken it abroad if we had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father in crowded clinics and hospitals, so that he could get any treatment he could benefit from.
“It’s not easy,” adds Mr. Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5 o’clock, rush to the hospital to be the first, and you’re not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation hasn’t changed much since Dr. Bwelle’s father died in 2002.
There is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants in Cameroon, according to the World Health Organization.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians would not be able to pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and three-quarters of the country’s health spending is made in the private sector.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” Dr Bwelle explained.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed over 700 free surgeries over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about thirty people, they get stuck in vanes after fixing medical equipment onto the roof and crossing difficult terrain to get to the villages that need help the most.
Luck does not always follow them.
They have repeatedly had to push vehicles to cross rivers or muddy trails.
But when they arrive, they are received as heroes: the community organizes a party, sings and dances and offers them the best accommodation available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr. Bwelle – with his great smile and overflowing energy – is more than happy to join the celebrations.
The next morning, the team began receiving hundreds of patients.
“We receive 500 people at each visit,” Bwelle said.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this traveling hospital, various health care services are provided.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get a wig, a pair of collected glasses, or a free birth certificate – a document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply can’t afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team practices simple surgical acts under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school, council or home; after the procedure, the patient stands up and goes to the wake-up room to leave his place to the next person.
Through the lighting of the electrogen group, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It’s a striking rhythm, but villagers’ musicians generally help the team stay motivated.
“They are knocking on the drums all night to keep us awake so we can continue to work,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, has practiced 700 surgeries for free over the past year, and they know that their presence can make a difference for those they come to help.
One man explained that the free operation he had undergone to cure a hernia would allow him to work again.
“It will change my future and that of my family,” the man said.
In addition to bringing this traveling hospital to life and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, which finances 60% of his association; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t know when he sleeps,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Dr. Bwelle’s group.
He is still in the hospital or trying to find money for his association so that he can conduct these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O’Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, this is an opportunity for field learning that they don’t have at home.
“We may have participated in operations to help sponge the blood or pass the instruments to Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley said.
This is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you are a second year medical student.
Volunteer students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their retirement, transportation and education are taken over by Dr. Bwelle.
“He’s a hero, there’s no doubt,” said Katie O’Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not close to fading.
For Dr Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a difficulty.
Helping others to live happily by keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle added.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons why I do this.
