John Kerry has admitted, unprecedentedly, that U.S. espionage “had gone too far in an inappropriate way.”
John Kerry said the United States’ defensive attitude toward its surveillance programs had risen, admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions, espionage had “goed too far in an inappropriate way.”
The Secretary of State also admitted that he had, like Barack Obama, ruled on “autopilot” when a series of fierce revelations by whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities occurred.
The leaks put the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Kerry said: “It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government have learned of certain things in automatic pilot mode because we had the opportunity to do so, from World War II to the difficult years of the Cold War, and then, of course, September 11.”
He then became the first senior member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed boundaries, but insisted that everyone’s rights had not been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it went too far in an inappropriate way.”
And the President is determined to try to clarify and clarify to people that he is now conducting a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels deceived.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Kerry, however, insisted that the NSA was a force working for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We live in a new world where people are ready to be blown up.”
There is radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We prevented planes from crashing, buildings from exploding, and people from being killed because we were able to know the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns over the alleged U.S. espionage case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint anti-terrorism efforts with the United States, the chairman of the Senate subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he spoke to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had uttered about a possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations due to the feeling of frustration aroused by the National Security Agency’s surveillance.
"It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans remain with us in our mutual commitment in the fight against terrorism," Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chairman of the U.S. Senate's European Affairs Subcommittee, said in an interview from Washington.
And I will travel to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger provoked by the NSA programs.
The press that the NSA captured millions of communications in Europe, which damaged relations with some U.S. allies, but the director of the agency said this week it was inaccurate and a misunderstanding as it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the U.S.
Other disclosures documents disclosed by Snowden that the NSA had intercepted data and communications from German Chancellor Angela Merkel’s mobile phones and those of 34 other heads of state.
Intelligence chief James Clapper justified allied espionage by saying it was necessary and common practice on both sides.
In this atmosphere of turmoil, Murphy indicated that his office was organising a congressional trip, which was scheduled to take place this year, and that he hoped that the delegation would include members from both parties and both houses.
The names of the other participating legislators are expected to be revealed in the coming days.
He said the route remains to be determined.
Murphy said the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show “affectionate firmness.”
He explained that European heads of state should be honest with their citizens about the type of espionage programs they have been implementing themselves for years.
“We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they must also understand that we are not the only ones in the world who do espionage,” Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Kerry plans to travel to the Middle East and Poland this weekend to deal with the resentment generated by U.S. strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as U.S. surveillance activities.
