Australian woman appeals on prison sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old resident of Sydney, who was sentenced to 15 days in prison in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been assaulted by a taxi driver, appealed the verdict and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was first found guilty by a Phuket Provincial Court on June 15 for false statements after telling Thai police that a local taxi driver, accompanied by two other men who controlled her, had assaulted her early on Sunday, June 10.
However, video surveillance recordings later revealed that she had safely returned to her hotel after separating from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interrogated Bamford for two days before it admitted to having invented the history of all rooms.
She was detained in a cell at the local police station before the hearing in court.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day prison sentence in a low-security detention center in the outskirts of Phuket rather than in a women’s prison.
It is the daughter of former Australian League rugby player Peter Tunks, who appealed to the Canberra Foreign Ministry to help his daughter.
Tunks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was “extremely concerned” about her daughter’s well-being and wanted her to return to Australia.
“We obviously lived through a troubling time, but we hope to bring her home safely as soon as possible,” Tunks said.
Bamford appealed the verdict and was released after paying a bail of 50,000 baht.
In Australia, the press said that in the meantime she was on vacation in the Krabi region in southern Thailand.
Thai judicial sources said Bamford was represented by a local Phuket lawyer, but warned that the appeal could lead to a heightened sentence of up to two years in prison and imprisonment in an adult prison.
